# Clean Code Principles

## General
IMPORTANT: Keep the code clean. Less is more. Simple is better than complex. Remove redundancies.

## Naming
- Names should reveal intent and purpose
- Avoid abbreviations unless universally understood
- Use consistent naming conventions

## Functions
- Single responsibility: one function, one job
- Keep functions small and focused (<60 lines)
- If a function needs explanation, split it

## Constants & Configuration
- Replace magic numbers with named constants
- Store configuration in config files or .env (single source of truth)

## Comments
- Code should be self-documenting
- Comment only to explain *why*, never *what*
- Documentn only non-obvious side effects and complex algorithms

## Structure
- DRY: extract repeated logic into reusable abstractions
- Keep related code together
- Hide implementation details, expose clear interfaces
- Move nested conditionals into well-named functions

## Anti-patterns to Avoid
- God classes (>300 lines)
- Nesting >2 levels deep
- Hardcoded configuration values

## Maintenance
- Fix technical debt early
- Leave code cleaner than you found it
